The Macedonian people voted on Sunday in a referendum to change their name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a movement that would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece and block admission requests to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would harm the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the result would achieve the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question that appeared on the referendum paper was: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for admission to entities such as the EU or NATO from Macedonia, one of the emerging countries of the fall of Yugoslavia.
“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although not legally binding, several members of parliament said they would abide by the result of the vote and make it final.
The change of nine would require a two-thirds majority of the parliament.
The State Election Commission stated that no irregularities had been recorded by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent of the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters filed their ballots.
"I have come to vote for my children, our site is in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko filed their vote for the Macedonian referendum on changing the name of the country that would pave the way for its accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents assembled for those who had boycotted the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with our heads high and not through the service door," Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favor because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of joining the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would take part in the referendum, a figure that is below the required.
Another survey conducted by Macedonian television network Telma indicated that 57 percent of the people surveyed planned to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For the referendum to be valid, the result must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would represent the first major blow to the pro-Western government's policy since it came to power in May.
