Scotland’s private schools maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing modern languages continue to be a popular and desired topic within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, that comes to mind.
But if you speak to him in his own language, it will reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year’s recent exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the board and with the highest approved rates in private schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who studied foreign languages gained an outstanding degree.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained honorary enrollment in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding score.
This demonstrates that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, languages are taking the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in programs of private schools and of all kinds.
A 2014 survey by the U.K. Commission for Employment and Training found that a lack of knowledge of languages constitutes 17% of the reasons why employers find it difficult to fill vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you learn a second language you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That’s why it’s so important to invest in a language for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, the language of instruction varies according to the school.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others opt for languages considered more important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your children, private schools always have several languages to choose from and teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that prepares children and staff with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
We cannot deny that at this time, in a global business environment, languages remain of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edwards is the director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
