While Ri resumed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as it had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean peninsula while Trump ensured North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first drop its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted relaxing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive-eight objective, and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke about three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other part of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a dead end.”
Still, Ri’s tone of speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the United Nations General Assembly it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim “a rocket man on a suicide mission.”
This year at the U.N., Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking steps to disarmament, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for that, and that “it takes two years, three or five months anyway.”
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “Enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we observe total, final and verified denuclearization.”
