Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
This year, a new Harvard University course is making all of its students sleep more in order to combat the growth of the male culture of caffeine-stimulated all-night study.
One academic found that students at the world’s number one university often miss the basics about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine and a specialist at Brigham and Muller Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact that lack of sleep had on learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are they only telling me this now, in my last year?’
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basic aspects of how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, trainers and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficiency affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are informed about how prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this information, just as we have the right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride to spend the whole night awake still exists, he says. And he adds that modern technology and the increasing pressure for students that involved lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you sleep enough and have a good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, it signals. Even avoiding fattening, as lack of sleep causes the brain to enter starvation mode, or which causes him to be hungry constantly.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for bedtime, as well as for when they wake up. Likewise, it is advisable that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic displays and LED lighting, which can imbalance the circadian rhythm and cause trouble sleeping.
