And now a page of our "Sunday Morning" almanach: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and CONTADO... was the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led him to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become a key element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring those seemingly unusual cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Home: "What is this in the world?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
By putting on these headphones, you can hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity of the minerals."
Evans: "Say, surely it's bursting right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name survives.
