Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report from the Florida Wildlife Conservation and Fisheries Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the said commission, increasingly uneven outcropping conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and in the counties of Collier, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern Pinellas counties to the southern Lee counties.
Concentrations can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsboroug County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
Reportedly, there were mid-level and off-shore concentrations in Pinellas County last week, bottom and high-shore concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom and high-shore concentrations in or off-shore Sarasota County, bottom and off-shore concentrations with low-shore and off-shore concentrations in Charlotte County, and low-shore and off-shore concentrationshore concentrations in Charlotte County.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
There have been no reports of such cases in northwest Florida over the past week.
